message.content: Quercus imbricaria, also known as Shingle Oak, is a deciduous tree that belongs to the Fagaceae family. It can grow up to 80 feet tall and can reach a width of 50 feet. The bark of the Shingle Oak is gray-brown and deeply ridged. The leaves of the Shingle Oak are leathery, dark green on top, and paler underneath. The leaves can be up to 8 inches long and have a distinct, wavy, and glossy margin. In the fall, the leaves turn a yellow-brown color before dropping. The Shingle Oak produces acorns that are about half an inch long and have a knobby cap. The Shingle Oak is commonly found in woodlands, along streams, and in urban areas.
